is the Kullback-Leibler divergence and it is used that formula_59.

Note: In order to derive the previous bounds, one has to start by observing that formula_60 where formula_61 are &quot;dependent&quot; random variables with a specific distribution formula_62. Because most of the theorems about bounds in sum of random variables are concerned with &quot;independent&quot; sequences of them, one has to first create a sequence formula_63 of &quot;independent&quot; random variables with the same distribution formula_62 and apply the theorems on formula_65. Then, it is proved from Hoeffding that the results and bounds obtained via this process hold for formula_19 as well.

If &quot;n&quot; is larger than &quot;N&quot;/2, it can be useful to apply symmetry to &quot;invert&quot; the bounds, which give you the following:

