== Statistical Inference ==
=== Hypergeometric test ===
The hypergeometric test uses the hypergeometric distribution to measure the statistical significance of having drawn a sample consisting of a specific number of formula_13 successes (out of formula_14 total draws) from a population of size formula_15 containing formula_16 successes. In a test for over-representation of successes in the sample, the hypergeometric p-value is calculated as the probability of randomly drawing formula_13 or more successes from the population in formula_14 total draws. In a test for under-representation, the p-value is the probability of randomly drawing formula_13 or fewer successes.

The test based on the hypergeometric distribution (hypergeometric test) is identical to the corresponding one-tailed version of Fisher&#x27;s exact test. Reciprocally, the p-value of a two-sided Fisher&#x27;s exact test can be calculated as the sum of two appropriate hypergeometric tests (for more information see).

The test is often used to identify which sub-populations are over- or under-represented in a sample. This test has a wide range of applications. For example, a marketing group could use the test to understand their customer base by testing a set of known customers for over-representation of various demographic subgroups (e.g., women, people under 30).

== Related distributions ==
Let formula_75 and formula_55.

*If formula_77 then formula_19 has a Bernoulli distribution with parameter formula_79.
*Let formula_80 have a binomial distribution with parameters formula_14 and formula_79; this models the number of successes in the analogous sampling problem &quot;with&quot; replacement. If formula_15 and formula_16 are large compared to formula_14, and formula_79 is not close to 0 or 1, then formula_19 and formula_80 have similar distributions, i.e., formula_89.
*If formula_14 is large, formula_15 and formula_16 are large compared to formula_14, and formula_79 is not close to 0 or 1, then
::formula_95

where formula_96 is the standard normal distribution function
* If the probabilities of drawing a green or red marble are not equal (e.g. because green marbles are bigger/easier to grasp than red marbles) then formula_19 has a noncentral hypergeometric distribution
* The beta-binomial distribution is a conjugate prior for the hypergeometric distribution.

The following table describes four distributions related to the number of successes in a sequence of draws: 
